[[edit](/w/index.php?title=Rust_(programming_language)&action=edit&section=49 "Edit section: Notes")]

1. **[↑](#cite_ref-3)** Including build tools, host tools, and standard library support for [x86-64](/wiki/X86-64 "X86-64"), [ARM](/wiki/ARM_architecture_family "ARM architecture family"), [MIPS](/wiki/MIPS_architecture "MIPS architecture"), [RISC-V](/wiki/RISC-V "RISC-V"), [WebAssembly](/wiki/WebAssembly "WebAssembly"), [i686](/wiki/P6_(microarchitecture) "P6 (microarchitecture)"), [AArch64](/wiki/AArch64 "AArch64"), [PowerPC](/wiki/PowerPC "PowerPC"), and [s390x](/wiki/Linux_on_IBM_Z "Linux on IBM Z").[[2]](#cite_note-CrossPlatform-2)
2. **[↑](#cite_ref-4)** Including [Windows](/wiki/Windows "Windows"), [Linux](/wiki/Linux "Linux"), [macOS](/wiki/MacOS "MacOS"), [FreeBSD](/wiki/FreeBSD "FreeBSD"), [NetBSD](/wiki/NetBSD "NetBSD"), and [Illumos](/wiki/Illumos "Illumos"). Host build tools on [Android](/wiki/Android_(operating_system) "Android (operating system)"), [iOS](/wiki/IOS "IOS"), [Haiku](/wiki/Haiku_(operating_system) "Haiku (operating system)"), [Redox](/wiki/Redox_(operating_system) "Redox (operating system)"), and [Fuchsia](/wiki/Fuchsia_(operating_system) "Fuchsia (operating system)") are not officially shipped; these operating systems are supported as
 targets.[[2]](#cite_note-CrossPlatform-2)
3. **[↑](#cite_ref-7)** Third-party dependencies, e.g., [LLVM](/wiki/LLVM "LLVM") or [MSVC](/wiki/MSVC "MSVC"), are
 subject to their own licenses.[[3]](#cite_note-5)[[4]](#cite_note-licenses-6)
4. **[↑](#cite_ref-10)** NIL is cited as an influence for Rust in multiple sources; this likely
 refers to Network Implementation Language developed by Robert Strom and
 others at [IBM](/wiki/IBM "IBM"), which pioneered [typestate analysis](/wiki/Typestate_analysis "Typestate analysis"),[[5]](#cite_note-Strom1983-8)[[6]](#cite_note-9) not to be confused with [New Implementation of LISP](/wiki/NIL_(programming_language) "NIL (programming language)").
5. **[↑](#cite_ref-23)** See previous footnote on the referent of NIL.
6. **[↑](#cite_ref-27)** The list of Rust compiler versions (referred to as a bootstrapping
 chain) has history going back to 2012.[[21]](#cite_note-Nelson2022RustConf-26)
7. **[↑](#cite_ref-36)** Energy compared to C was 3% more for Rust and 34% more for C++; time
 was 4% more and 56% more, respectively.
8. **[↑](#cite_ref-140)** wrapping `no_mangle` with `unsafe` as well as prefacing the `extern "C"` block with `unsafe` are required in the 2024 edition or later.[[132]](#cite_note-139)
9. **[↑](#cite_ref-200)** That is, among respondents who have done "extensive development work
 [with Rust] in over the past year" (14.8%), Rust had the largest
 percentage who also expressed interest to "work in [Rust] over the next
 year" (72.4%).[[190]](#cite_note-SO-2025-survey-198)

